TY  - JOUR
AB  - We show that in an open-economy OLG model, the interaction between growth differentials and household credit constraints&#x2014;more severe in fast-growing countries&#x2014;can explain three prominent global trends: a divergence in private saving rates between advanced and emerging economies, large net capital outflows from the latter, and a sustained decline in the world interest rate. Micro-level evidence on the evolution of age-saving profiles in the US and China corroborates our mechanism. Quantitatively, our model explains about a third of the divergence in aggregate saving rates, and a significant portion of the variations in age-saving profiles across countries and over time.
